== Overview ==

[[File:造山1号墳出土 円筒埴輪 (J-34492).JPG|thumb|160px|right|{{center|Cylindrical haniwa from Tsukuriyama 1 Kofun}}{{small|Exhibited at {{ill|Tokyo National Museum|ja|東京国立博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.}}]]
'''Tsukuriyama 1 Kofun''' is a {{ill|square-shaped Kofun|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} measuring 60 meters on each side, one of the largest square mounds from the early Kofun period nationwide. Excavations in {{ill|1936|ja|昭和|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Shōwa 11) and 1938 (Shōwa 13) revealed a {{ill|pit-style stone chamber|ja|竪穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=竪穴式石室|4=zh|5=豎穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Buried artifacts include {{ill|triangular-rimmed deity-and-beast mirrors|ja|三角縁神獣鏡|1=Triangular-Rimmed Divine Beast Mirror|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|TLV mirror|lt=square-rim deity-and-animal mirrors|ja|方格規矩鏡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, spindle-shaped stone artifacts, glass {{ill|tubular beads|ja|管玉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, iron swords, and {{ill|ko-dachi|ja|刀子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. On December 16, 1936, it was designated a National Historic Site under the name "Tsukuriyama Kofun."{{Sfn|Nagami|Miyake|1992|p=1}}

'''Tsukuriyama 3 Kofun''' is a square mound dating to the early Kofun period, measuring 38 meters in length and 30 meters in width. Excavations in {{ill|1965|ja|昭和40|qq=draft|qq=draft}} uncovered a pit-style stone chamber yielding a {{ill|two-deity two-beast mirror|ja|斜縁神獣鏡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, jasper tubular beads, glass beads, a ko-dachi, and a yari-ganna. It was designated a Shimane Prefecture Historic Site on May 31, 1965.{{Sfn|Nagami|Miyake|1992|p=1}}

On the highest point of the hill, there is '''Tsukuriyama 2 Kofun''', a {{ill|keyhole-shaped mound|ja|前方後方墳|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} measuring 50 meters in length, and the smaller '''Tsukuriyama 4 Kofun'''. Both were excavated in 1991, revealing construction dating to the early 6th century.{{Sfn|Nagami|Miyake|1992}} A fifth mound, '''Tsukuriyama 5 Kofun''', is located slightly apart from the main group.

Nearby, the '''Ōnari Kofun''', another square mound from the early Kofun period, is the largest of its kind nationally. Excavations in {{ill|1911|ja|明治44|qq=draft|qq=draft}} revealed artifacts such as triangular-rimmed deity-and-beast mirrors and a {{ill|sokantō|ja|素環頭大刀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. A reproduction of the sokantō, crafted by master swordsmith {{ill|Kawachi Kunihira|ja|河内国平|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, is exhibited at the {{ill|Yasugi City Wako Museum|ja|和鋼博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== Cultural Properties ==
Initially, Tsukuriyama 1 Kofun was designated as a National Historic Site, and Tsukuriyama 3 Kofun was designated as a Shimane Prefecture Historic Site. In 1999, the Agency for Cultural Affairs expanded the designation to include Tsukuriyama Kofun Group (2-4 Kofun), Ōnari Kofun, and the Shiozuyama Burial Group (1-11 Kofun), officially renaming them the "'''Arashima Kofun Group'''".<ref name=shimanebunkazai/><ref name=bunkaisan/>

